June 4, 2026

****Market Performance****

****Trending on TIKR****

Broadcom (NASDAQ: AVGO) https://app.tikr.com/stock/about?cid=3D25016048&tid=
=3D555183874: Broadcom is set to open lower this morning after its fiscal s=
econd-quarter report. Revenue rose about 48% from a year ago to roughly $22=
.2 billion, just shy of estimates, while adjusted profit edged ahead. AI re=
venue more than doubled to around $10.8 billion, and management guided this=
 quarter's AI revenue to roughly triple, to about $16 billion. The drop cam=
e after CEO Hock Tan declined to lift the $100 billion-plus AI sales target=
 and said the company would sell chips only, not full systems. After a near=
-ninefold run since 2022, simply meeting sky-high expectations wasn't enoug=
h.

Abivax (NASDAQ: ABVX) https://app.tikr.com/stock/about?cid=3D256839883&tid=
=3D303237911: Abivax bounced about 24% after a brutal drop of more than 40%=
 the prior day. The French biotech makes an experimental oral drug for ulce=
rative colitis, a chronic inflammation of the colon, and just posted strong=
 late-stage results: roughly half of patients in remission at 44 weeks vers=
us about 10% on placebo. So why the crash? The same data flagged a few canc=
er cases in the higher-dose group, raising a safety worry even though the c=
ompany called them unrelated. Wednesday's rebound reflects bargain-hunters =
and bulls (one firm lifted its target to $187) betting the scare is overdon=
e.

Sterling Infrastructure (NASDAQ: STRL): https://app.tikr.com/stock/about?ci=
d=3D322372&tid=3D2654656 Sterling climbed about 9% as data-center construct=
ion stocks rallied. The company does the heavy site work that comes before =
the servers: clearing land, grading, foundations, and utilities for data ce=
nters and other big facilities. That "e-infrastructure" business is now the=
 bulk of revenue and grew well over 100% last quarter, with backlog up near=
 $3.8 billion and full-year revenue guided around $3.1 billion. The move wa=
s part of a broader bid for the picks-and-shovels of the AI buildout. With =
hyperscalers still pouring money into capacity, investors are increasingly =
willing to pay up for the companies pouring the concrete, not just the chip=
makers.

Intuitive Machines (NASDAQ: LUNR): https://app.tikr.com/stock/about?cid=3D7=
10155302&tid=3D1821744038 Intuitive Machines fell roughly 15% after announc=
ing a big stock sale. The space company builds robotic landers and provides=
 services for NASA (it put the first private spacecraft on the Moon in 2024=
), and it filed to sell up to $500 million in shares through an at-the-mark=
et program. Investors read that as dilution: more shares outstanding means =
each existing share owns a thinner slice of the company. It lands while Int=
uitive is still burning cash and spending heavily, despite a backlog above =
$1 billion from government work.

Oklo (NYSE: OKLO): https://app.tikr.com/stock/about?cid=3D544611249&tid=3D1=
880674355 Oklo slid about 11% as speculative nuclear and power names sold o=
ff together. Oklo is a pre-revenue startup developing small modular reactor=
s, compact nuclear plants designed to deliver round-the-clock electricity t=
o data centers and other heavy power users. It has plenty of cash but no op=
erating reactor yet, with first deployments still a couple of years out. Th=
e drop was part of a broader pullback in AI-power plays after an enormous r=
un, as investors turned pickier about which names can actually convert spla=
shy contracts into revenue.

