**SailPoint (NASDAQ: SAIL): Why Analysts Are Forecasting Revenue to More Th=
an Double to Roughly $2.3 Billion by 2031**

SailPoint sells identity security software, the systems that decide who ins=
ide a company is allowed to open which files, apps, and databases, and that=
 flag anyone holding access they shouldn't have. It returned to the public =
market in early 2025 after a few years owned by private equity, so the busi=
ness trading today is leaner and far more cloud-focused than the one that l=
isted years ago.

Analysts expect revenue to climb from about $1.1 billion in the fiscal year=
 just ended to roughly $2.3 billion by early 2031, growth of around 19% a y=
ear, with profit margins widening along the way.

https://app.tikr.com/stock/about?cid=3D1917238503&tid=3D1929988473=20

A few forces drive that outlook. The biggest is AI: every AI agent, softwar=
e bot, and machine account needs permission to act, just like an employee, =
and these non-human identities now outnumber humans inside many companies. =
They made up about a quarter of SailPoint's cloud identity growth last quar=
ter, and revenue from customers buying its AI tools jumped more than 50%. A=
 second driver is the move to cloud software. SailPoint still has roughly $=
350 million of older, on-premise licenses to migrate onto its cloud platfor=
m, and management says those customers tend to spend two to three times mor=
e once they switch. Underpinning both is a sticky, recurring model: about $=
1.1 billion in annual recurring revenue growing near 28%, with roughly 97% =
of customers renewing each year.

The forecast looks credible because the core cloud-subscription engine is a=
lready accelerating on its own, and the wave of AI-driven identities expand=
s SailPoint's market rather than just reshuffling demand it already had.

